LOCATION: src/delivery.rs line 271; src/relay.rs lines 112-117, 194-203; src/server.rs lines 1075-1080

FINDING: Multiple sites follow this pattern:
  let parsed = url::Url::parse(&uri);
  let path = parsed.as_ref().map(|u| u.path().to_string()).unwrap_or_else(|_| "/inbox".to_string());
  let host = parsed.as_ref().ok().and_then(|u| u.host_str().map(|h| h.to_string())).unwrap_or_default();

url::Url::path() and host_str() return &str borrows from the Url. Calling .to_string() on them is only needed because the Url is not kept alive. The idiomatic fix is to bind the Url to a named variable and extract &str references before it goes out of scope — no allocation needed for path or host in the success case.

IMPACT: Two String allocations per outbound delivery (path + host). These are dwarfed by the HTTP roundtrip, but the pattern is repeated 4+ times and is an ownership/borrowing idiom issue.
